"/> Nope. The &quot;ye&quot; in &quot;Ye olde Englisshe Antique Shop&quot; is still pronounced
&quot;the&quot; (sometimes &quot;thee&quot; depending on the letter following it.)

The reason why is that it's really not a &quot;y&quot; at all. It's a thorn, an
letter used in Old English, Middle English, and the first part of Early
Modern English. We used to render by typing a &quot;b&quot; over a &quot;p&quot; -- that is,
it has a slightly uptilted round part sticking out from an upright that
goes both high and low. (Dang, sometimes the rule against pictures in
newsgroups makes explanation very hard.)

When formerly handwritten alphabets were translated to type, at first the
type did its best to imitate handwriting, so you would have the short &quot;s&quot;
in the beginning of words and the long &quot;s&quot; that looks like an &quot;f&quot; in the
middle, the &quot;r&quot; that we use now in most places, but the &quot;r&quot; that looks
like a &quot;2&quot; before round letters. You know, all the variations. As time
passed, type was simplified to not imitate handwriting quite so much, but
some abbreviations were kept.

Even though the spelling reformers of the 18C managed to replace the
thorn with &quot;th&quot; in most places, it held on, especially at the beginning
of a sentence for quite a long time, because, let's face it, it is more
graceful.

And then, when people started getting romantic about the past (quite a
fad for Anglo-Saxon [= Old English] in the seventeenth century) people
would write &quot;ye&quot; for &quot;the&quot; because it looks more like the thorn-e (see
the history post that started all this for beautifully rendered thorns).
And then people started pronouncing it &quot;ye&quot; out of pure ignorance.

Which brings us up to the present.

So, properly &quot;ye olde Englisshe coffee-shoppe&quot; should be pronounced &quot;the
old English coffee-shop&quot; but if you are being silly or cutesy (which none
of us in rec.antiques ever is), you would say &quot;ye oldie Englishy
coffee-shoppy.&quot;

Tish
